    "catalysts": [],
    "industrial_process_notes": "Not industrially polymerized -- extracted from brown seaweed (Phaeophyceae), particularly giant kelp (Macrocystis pyrifera), Ascophyllum nodosum, and Laminaria species (some bacteria, e.g. Pseudomonas and Azotobacter, also produce alginates). Edward Charles Cortis Stanford discovered alginate and patented an extraction process in 1881. Modern extraction converts the seaweed's alginic acid/calcium alginate to soluble sodium alginate; newer methods under investigation include microwave-, ultrasound-, and enzyme-assisted extraction.",
